                     <interp inst="t18160110-59-person607" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             said he had attended on Mr. Teasdale, as Solicitor for the London Dock Company, and told him what the transaction was.</p>
               <p>Q. What he said he thought was no harm was his signing his principal's name without his principal's knowledge - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. And he said, what he had done he did without the least intention to defraud any one - A. He did.</p>
               <p>A long tissue of documentary evidence, from the books of the London Dock Company, and parcel evidence was gone into, and which is unimportant here to repeat, to prove that Mr. Tnglis was the treasurer of the London Dock Company, both at the time of the commission of this forgery, and also at the time of the present trial. However, the gentlemen engaged for the prosecution relied mainly on the proof of his being treasurer, upon the evidence of 
               <persName id="t18160110-59-person608">
